103
00:03:52,535 --> 00:03:52,788
Scott: A cook.

104
00:03:53,271 --> 00:03:53,989
Rym: Not necessarily.

105
00:03:54,270 --> 00:03:57,950
Rym: Perhaps he simply loves to eat cupcakes, but not to bake cupcakes.

106
00:03:57,950 --> 00:03:59,846
Scott: He can bake and eat the cupcakes together.

107
00:04:00,690 --> 00:04:02,030
Rym: But see, I think here's the problem.

108
00:04:02,350 --> 00:04:10,390
Rym: People who love food enough to review food, who also learn to be professional chefs, die of obesity immediately.

109
00:04:10,530 --> 00:04:11,230
Scott: That's what I'm saying.

110
00:04:11,370 --> 00:04:12,170
Scott: There's a feedback loop.

111
00:04:12,390 --> 00:04:18,890
Rym: So thus, the people who are smart enough to not learn to cook are the only people who can survive being food critics.

112
00:04:19,391 --> 00:04:25,210
Scott: Right, but things that I know about, like technology and gaming, I see these journalists writing about gaming or technology.

113
00:04:25,471 --> 00:04:30,210
Scott: And I bet to normal people, they sound like they really know what they're talking about.

114
00:04:30,290 --> 00:04:39,550
