115
00:04:39,850 --> 00:04:44,228
Rym: Well, according to a lot of developers we've talked to, we think about games way more than they do.

116
00:04:45,371 --> 00:04:46,850
Scott: The journalists don't know anything.

117
00:04:46,930 --> 00:04:54,510
Scott: So this is probably some tech guy who, you know, if he knew more about technology, he would be a technologist and not a technology journalist.

118
00:04:54,510 --> 00:04:54,967
Rym: Maybe he is.

119
00:04:55,130 --> 00:04:56,570
Rym: What about people like John C. Dvorak?

120
00:04:56,730 --> 00:04:57,082
Rym: He knows a lot.

121
00:04:57,510 --> 00:04:58,249
Scott: He doesn't know nearly.

122
00:04:58,430 --> 00:04:58,886
Scott: No, he doesn't.

123
00:04:59,390 --> 00:04:59,989
Rym: Let me put it this way.

124
00:05:00,310 --> 00:05:03,022
Scott: He knows more about technology companies than actual computers.

125
00:05:05,070 --> 00:05:09,330
Rym: John C. Dvorak has a great breadth of knowledge in the techno industry at large.

126
00:05:09,390 --> 00:05:10,029
Rym: It's very shallow.

127
00:05:10,370 --> 00:05:15,150
Rym: It is very shallow, but it is very breadthful and I can't disrespect him for that.

128
00:05:15,470 --> 00:05:23,310
Scott: But the thing is, most of those guys, he doesn't know about, you know, I mean, he knows enough about computers that he can use them and set them up and do all sorts of normal people things.

129
00:05:23,370 --> 00:05:26,250
Rym: He also knows effectively how to troll.

130
00:05:27,230 --> 00:05:30,330
Scott: But I mean, and he knows a lot about, you know, the tech companies.

131
00:05:30,992 --> 00:05:38,410
Scott: And if he was writing an article about computers, it would go in the business section of the newspaper, not in the, you know, technology section of the newspaper.

132
00:05:38,490 --> 00:05:41,450
Rym: But he has more knowledge of tech than the vast majority of tech journalists.

133
00:05:42,196 --> 00:05:42,709
Scott: Yeah, it's true.

134
00:05:43,491 --> 00:05:47,208
Scott: But I mean, he's not going to be writing anything for like the ACM Journal or the IEEE, you.

135
00:05:47,770 --> 00:05:50,810
Rym: But I have for you a counterexample and then an anecdote.

136
00:05:51,392 --> 00:06:01,930
Rym: Because the counterexample is that in the financial sector, I read articles on financial stuff and those people know way more than me or most other people in the field about the field.

137
00:06:02,130 --> 00:06:02,706
Scott: They know a lot.

138
00:06:02,970 --> 00:06:05,150
Scott: Then how come they're doing that instead of making mad money?

139
00:06:05,390 --> 00:06:10,970
Rym: They're making pretty good money because usually the people who are writing the things that I'm reading are also published academics.

140
00:06:12,271 --> 00:06:20,430
Rym: Anyway, the anecdotal evidence I have is that when I was sick of working at the hospital and I thought about giving up on IT completely, that was when I went to take the LSAT.

141
00:06:20,755 --> 00:06:21,729
Rym: I was like, I'll be a lawyer.

142
00:06:22,110 --> 00:06:23,929
Rym: And all the lawyer friends were like, God, no, you'll hate it.

143
00:06:24,371 --> 00:06:26,209
Rym: And then I was like, OK, I'll be a journalist.

144
00:06:26,451 --> 00:06:28,790
Rym: And I actually applied to a bunch of tech journalism jobs.

145
00:06:29,431 --> 00:06:35,209
Rym: And I ghostwrote for a bunch of tech journals and websites because that's how you interview for places like that.

146
00:06:35,510 --> 00:06:39,490
Rym: You ghostwrite articles for them that they publish so they don't have to do work.

147
00:06:39,610 --> 00:06:40,710
Rym: They get free work, basically.

148
00:06:41,471 --> 00:06:46,449
Rym: So I got my assignments and I wrote and basically the assignments were pathetic.

149
00:06:47,354 --> 00:06:50,330
Rym: They were along the lines of X is popular.

150
00:06:50,890 --> 00:06:57,409
Scott: Write an article about how Y influences X so that we can get increase the search engine traffic as most people are searching for X.

151
00:06:57,855 --> 00:06:58,048
Rym: Yep.

152
00:06:58,330 --> 00:06:58,506
Scott: Yep.

153
00:06:58,971 --> 00:07:02,670
Rym: And basically the vast majority of tech journalism seems to be that.

154
00:07:03,132 --> 00:07:05,048
Rym: And I after interviewing these people.

155
00:07:05,712 --> 00:07:06,387
Rym: Yeah, I gave up.

156
00:07:06,637 --> 00:07:06,809
Rym: Yeah.

157
00:07:06,910 --> 00:07:10,789
Rym: Well, I don't think Wired magazine exactly has the hard hitting tech writers either.

158
00:07:11,334 --> 00:07:12,670
Scott: It has a few, but not many.

159
00:07:12,891 --> 00:07:24,229
Rym: So anyway, this dude, Galen Gruman, wrote this thing where he basically says that wireless network infrastructure is being neglected and it needs to be the core.

160
00:07:24,890 --> 00:07:31,165
Rym: It needs to be as well managed, as important, as central to enterprise as the wired network needs to be.

161
00:07:31,992 --> 00:07:33,290
Scott: And in what way does he mean that?

162
00:07:33,370 --> 00:07:35,710
Scott: Does he mean like the backbone of the Internet should be wireless?

163
00:07:35,970 --> 00:07:36,241
Rym: No, no, no.

164
00:07:36,490 --> 00:07:41,190
Rym: So he has all these statistics, which I am highly half of them.

165
00:07:41,250 --> 00:07:41,590
Rym: I'm dubious.

166
00:07:41,752 --> 00:07:43,350
Rym: I just don't think they're accurate.

167
00:07:43,730 --> 00:07:43,823
Rym: Okay.

168
00:07:43,970 --> 00:07:55,950
Scott: And the other half, even if they're accurate, he is begging the question and drawing the absolute wrong conclusion, because I do think that a lot of enterprise people either a, they don't have wireless at all for security reasons.

169
00:07:56,670 --> 00:07:57,187
Rym: They don't need it.

170
00:07:57,350 --> 00:08:00,950
Scott: Well, I think that there are some significant benefits to having it.

171
00:08:01,050 --> 00:08:10,630
Scott: Even if you don't need it, it could be significantly beneficial and it is possible to make it secure enough as long as you don't use it, you know, for as long as you fence it off from certain applications.

172
00:08:10,630 --> 00:08:10,820
Scott: Right.

173
00:08:11,110 --> 00:08:17,890
Scott: It's like if people can get their exchange, their emails on their phones with Wi-Fi walking around the office.

174
00:08:18,610 --> 00:08:20,830
Rym: Ah, but so here's that's worse.

175
00:08:21,030 --> 00:08:21,200
Rym: Yes.

176
00:08:21,550 --> 00:08:31,009
Rym: One of the examples he uses is the rapid growth of smartphones and how many people have smartphones that have Wi-Fi capabilities and how if they could use those on the wireless network, things would be so much better.

177
00:08:31,850 --> 00:08:43,289
Rym: Yet the vast majority of what anyone does with a smartphone in any professional context is read email, get pages, respond to email and pages.

178
00:08:43,702 --> 00:08:43,890
Scott: Yep.

179
00:08:44,111 --> 00:08:45,627
Rym: You can do that over your three G's.

180
00:08:46,291 --> 00:08:57,290
Scott: Ah, but actually if I was enterprise and I'm worried about security, I would rather have if those things going over the Wi-Fi in my company on my company's network, then going over the three G of AT&T or something like that.

181
00:08:57,310 --> 00:09:03,850
Rym: But the Wi-Fi, so having the secure Wi-Fi would be pointless because the only reason to have one of those devices is because you're leaving the office.

182
00:09:04,093 --> 00:09:05,249
Rym: You're going somewhere else.

183
00:09:05,411 --> 00:09:09,010
Scott: Yes, but at least more of the traffic that has the email.

184
00:09:09,350 --> 00:09:12,730
Rym: Nope, because no one uses their goddamn Blackberry when they're in the office.

185
00:09:13,050 --> 00:09:13,430
Scott: Yeah, they do.

186
00:09:13,550 --> 00:09:14,990
Rym: Whoo, their computer's there.

187
00:09:15,390 --> 00:09:19,630
Scott: You go look at any office that just people walking around the offices with Blackberries.

188
00:09:19,890 --> 00:09:20,190
Rym: You know what?

189
00:09:20,410 --> 00:09:26,830
Scott: I don't know what offices you've been to, but that's all I see when people are walking and anyone who gets up to walk around in the bathroom, phones are in their hands are looking at it.

190
00:09:26,890 --> 00:09:27,549
Rym: See, I've seen that.

191
00:09:27,670 --> 00:09:27,950
Rym: You know what?

192
00:09:28,310 --> 00:09:29,810
Scott: In conference rooms, Blackberries all over the table.

193
00:09:29,890 --> 00:09:39,708
Rym: The only people who are ever checking their email on their Blackberries in the offices were the mid-level executives, and most of the people I see walking around with a phone have a web page up.

194
00:09:40,152 --> 00:09:42,090
Scott: I see everybody from top to bottom doing that.

195
00:09:42,331 --> 00:09:42,969
Rym: I don't see that.

196
00:09:43,110 --> 00:09:49,370
Rym: Of course, I've always worked in big enterprise where it's a very different environment, but nonetheless, I don't think there's any benefit to people.

197
00:09:49,950 --> 00:09:53,650
Rym: Plus, most Blackberries don't handle connecting to WANs gracefully.

198
00:09:54,130 --> 00:09:55,090
Scott: Well, who's using a Blackberry?

199
00:09:55,230 --> 00:09:56,210
Scott: Most enterprise users.

200
00:09:56,450 --> 00:09:57,430
Scott: I know, that's your other problem.

201
00:09:57,610 --> 00:09:58,789
Scott: Trash your Blackberry server.

202
00:09:59,652 --> 00:10:02,610
Scott: Use Exchange and get Windows or Android or iPhones.

203
00:10:02,753 --> 00:10:03,690
Rym: Now, we've talked about this.

204
00:10:03,850 --> 00:10:09,590
Rym: The plausible deniability of using Blackberry basically protects you from all possible litigation in the event of a problem.

205
00:10:09,850 --> 00:10:11,990
Scott: What's not plausibly deniable about an Exchange server?

206
00:10:12,130 --> 00:10:14,290
Rym: Hardly anyone uses that on phones for enterprise.

207
00:10:15,557 --> 00:10:16,149
Scott: It will change.

208
00:10:16,510 --> 00:10:16,686
Scott: It works.

209
00:10:17,150 --> 00:10:17,590
Rym: It will change.

