363
00:19:13,690 --> 00:19:20,310
Rym: Is it ethical to ask for a finder's fee for finding an undisclosed, unknown vulnerability in someone's software?

364
00:19:20,310 --> 00:19:21,836
Scott: Well, you're wording it differently.

365
00:19:22,036 --> 00:19:24,987
Scott: Is it extorting or is it blackmailing or is it finder's fee?

366
00:19:25,007 --> 00:19:25,730
Scott: It's the same thing.

367
00:19:25,970 --> 00:19:26,611
Rym: Well, is it though?

368
00:19:26,631 --> 00:19:27,433
Rym: Here's my question.

369
00:19:28,214 --> 00:19:35,910
Rym: Is it a crime or should it be a crime to disclose truth that you acquired through legal means?

370
00:19:36,430 --> 00:19:39,201
Scott: Well, I mean, if they just disclose it, you know, I mean, people have done that.

371
00:19:39,221 --> 00:19:40,205
Scott: I don't really have a problem with that.

372
00:19:40,285 --> 00:19:41,289
Scott: It's the extorting of money.

373
00:19:42,613 --> 00:19:44,617
Rym: This is why it's an interesting argument.

374
00:19:44,958 --> 00:19:50,050
Rym: So it is OK to disclose a vulnerability that I find through legal means like it is ethically.

375
00:19:50,713 --> 00:19:52,304
Rym: You can't fault someone for telling the truth.

376
00:19:52,344 --> 00:19:52,908
Rym: Is that correct?

377
00:19:52,989 --> 00:19:53,190
Scott: Right.

378
00:19:53,650 --> 00:20:00,130
Rym: So is it ethical to tell someone else who could fix it and who is affected by it that it exists?

379
00:20:01,791 --> 00:20:04,567
Scott: This vulnerability, you could you could tell anyone whatever you want.

