00:48:15,230 --> 00:48:15,351
Rym: Yeah.

973
00:48:15,391 --> 00:48:21,990
Rym: You write a special browser that handles, you know, memory management is very different on a compact device or device where power usage matters.

974
00:48:23,292 --> 00:48:28,393
Scott: The other thing is that there are programs out there that have what are called memory leaks.

975
00:48:28,917 --> 00:48:29,158
Scott: Right.

976
00:48:29,219 --> 00:48:30,750
Scott: And this is this is kind of a situation.

977
00:48:30,850 --> 00:48:30,951
Scott: Right.

978
00:48:30,971 --> 00:48:38,750
Scott: When you're writing a program, if you're writing in Java or Python or something like that, there is an automatic system called a garbage collector.

979
00:48:38,951 --> 00:48:43,393
Scott: And what this does is, you know, as you're programming, you're making a variable, putting it in memory.

980
00:48:44,620 --> 00:48:46,690
Scott: You're using it and then maybe you don't need it anymore.

981
00:48:46,851 --> 00:48:49,190
Scott: And you go on to use some other variables or some objects.

982
00:48:49,331 --> 00:48:49,552
Scott: Right.

983
00:48:49,592 --> 00:48:52,891
Scott: And maybe you load some data from a database, use it, and then you don't need it anymore.

984
00:48:53,353 --> 00:48:57,470
Scott: Well, if you're writing in Java or Python or any garbage collected language.

985
00:48:57,751 --> 00:48:57,993
Scott: Right.

986
00:48:58,275 --> 00:49:00,470
Scott: Those things that you don't need anymore that are in memory.

987
00:49:00,911 --> 00:49:04,890
Scott: Will slowly but surely be removed from memory by the garbage collector.

988
00:49:05,370 --> 00:49:05,712
Scott: Right.

989
00:49:05,732 --> 00:49:10,556
Scott: So that, you know, your program, you know, won't, you know, slowly grow and grow and grow for no reason.

990
00:49:10,576 --> 00:49:13,030
Scott: It'll only grow as far as it needs to grow.

991
00:49:13,311 --> 00:49:13,593
Scott: Right.

992
00:49:13,633 --> 00:49:16,370
Scott: You know, you won't be like, oh, here's a card that I'm going to use once.

993
00:49:16,490 --> 00:49:21,142
Scott: There's a one used metro card and I'm going to leave that one used metro card in my wallet forever, even though I used it once already.

994
00:49:21,464 --> 00:49:22,330
Scott: that it doesn't do that.

995
00:49:22,490 --> 00:49:22,694
Scott: It's not.

996
00:49:22,755 --> 00:49:23,609
Scott: it's smart enough not to.

997
00:49:23,750 --> 00:49:36,450
Scott: But if you write a program and say C, C++, Objective C, some sort of non garbage collected compiled language, you as the program or when you're writing this program need to manually manage the memory.

998
00:49:36,630 --> 00:49:42,393
Scott: You need to specifically code, you know, take this data, put it in the memory, do a bunch of stuff.

999
00:49:42,514 --> 00:49:45,650
Scott: Now take that data and remove it from the memory.

1000
00:49:45,730 --> 00:49:47,550
Scott: You need to actually code that specific thing.

1001
00:49:48,012 --> 00:49:48,213
Scott: Right.

1002
00:49:48,294 --> 00:49:50,650
Scott: In Java, you don't need to ever say remove that from the memory.

1003
00:49:50,650 --> 00:49:52,389
Scott: You can now, but you don't want to.

1004
00:49:52,690 --> 00:49:57,070
Rym: At the same time, many, many Java written applications have huge memory leaks.

1005
00:49:57,271 --> 00:49:59,090
Scott: Well, that's a that's a different problem altogether.

1006
00:49:59,090 --> 00:50:05,409
Rym: Well, that's just due to the fact that people effectively will leave objects open in a context where they could still be used.

1007
00:50:05,832 --> 00:50:06,034
Rym: Yeah.

1008
00:50:06,175 --> 00:50:07,850
Rym: And thus will never be garbage collected.

1009
00:50:08,331 --> 00:50:13,672
Rym: And thus through every iteration of a loop, a new object, object, object, object, object, object.

1010
00:50:13,792 --> 00:50:23,309
Scott: It is possible to make a memory leak in a garbage collected environment, but it is more common that it will happen in a non garbage collecting environment regardless because you're relying on fallible humans.

1011
00:50:23,670 --> 00:50:23,750
Scott: Yes.

1012
00:50:23,831 --> 00:50:31,150
Scott: It is possible to write a program that will just fill up the memory slowly but surely with stuff that is not needed in the memory.

1013
00:50:31,610 --> 00:50:37,609
Scott: And then what will happen is your whole computer will slow to a crawl once it runs out of memory and can't remove anything from the memory.

1014
00:50:37,871 --> 00:50:40,310
Scott: What's interesting is because the program is written poorly.

1015
00:50:40,731 --> 00:50:42,139
Rym: What's interesting is a lot of people.

1016
00:50:42,180 --> 00:50:43,770
Rym: this is kind of a more technical aside.

1017
00:50:44,570 --> 00:50:46,770
Rym: Windows and Linux handle the situation very differently.

1018
00:50:47,030 --> 00:50:55,290
Rym: And I realized looking at the Internet for some unrelated thing that many people have encountered something scary in the Linux world.

1019
00:50:55,732 --> 00:51:00,490
Rym: They'll be using their computer and it slows down and suddenly shit starts crashing.

1020
00:51:00,930 --> 00:51:01,010
Scott: Yeah.

1021
00:51:01,192 --> 00:51:04,270
Rym: And they look in varlog messages or usually they didn't configure logging.

1022
00:51:04,450 --> 00:51:04,570
Rym: Right.

1023
00:51:04,872 --> 00:51:09,210
Rym: So the console starts writing this line OOM killer invoked.

1024
00:51:09,530 --> 00:51:09,771
Scott: Yeah.

1025
00:51:09,892 --> 00:51:14,973
Scott: So Linux in the kernel has a thing called the OOM killer out of memory, the out of memory killer.

1026
00:51:15,014 --> 00:51:22,850
Scott: And what it does is when your computer runs out of memory and runs out of swap space so it can't even do the page thrashing to the disk anymore.

1027
00:51:23,214 --> 00:51:24,630
Scott: It is literally out of memory.

1028
00:51:24,751 --> 00:51:26,209
Scott: It usually has nowhere to go.

1029
00:51:26,650 --> 00:51:36,590
Rym: Usually happens when you've got an application that is crashing in such a way, which is actually fairly common, especially with demons that are poorly written or that do something very intensive like market data handlers.

1030
00:51:37,190 --> 00:51:39,810
Scott: Or someone has like an infinite fork loop that they wrote in a bash.

1031
00:51:39,850 --> 00:51:42,570
Rym: They'll get out of control and just fill the RAM in the space of a second.

1032
00:51:42,810 --> 00:51:42,930
Scott: Yeah.

1033
00:51:43,392 --> 00:51:48,210
Scott: What Linux will do is it will based on priorities, this prioritizing algorithm.

1034
00:51:48,410 --> 00:51:49,890
Rym: It's semi random in some cases.

1035
00:51:50,230 --> 00:51:50,374
Scott: Semi.

1036
00:51:50,395 --> 00:51:50,889
Scott: It depends.

1037
00:51:51,070 --> 00:51:51,172
Scott: Right.

1038
00:51:51,192 --> 00:51:52,110
Scott: You can go look up the algorithm.

1039
00:51:52,171 --> 00:51:53,290
Rym: I don't even know the algorithm.

1040
00:51:53,391 --> 00:51:55,090
Scott: It will pick a process.

1041
00:51:55,290 --> 00:51:58,170
Scott: It'll pick something that is using memory and kill it.

1042
00:51:58,290 --> 00:52:07,950
Scott: So let's say you've got Firefox and Apache server and an instant message client and an evil thing and my SQL server.

1043
00:52:08,171 --> 00:52:10,269
Rym: Never mind the million other things that are running in the back.

1044
00:52:10,470 --> 00:52:10,552
Scott: Yeah.

1045
00:52:10,573 --> 00:52:11,230
Scott: And they're all running.

1046
00:52:11,592 --> 00:52:11,814
Scott: Right.

1047
00:52:11,854 --> 00:52:13,710
Scott: And suddenly your computer runs out of memory.

1048
00:52:13,911 --> 00:52:14,153
Scott: Right.

1049
00:52:14,374 --> 00:52:16,910
Scott: The Linux kernel will be just like my SQL.

1050
00:52:17,652 --> 00:52:18,257
Scott: I pick you.

1051
00:52:18,479 --> 00:52:19,869
Scott: You are now gone and it just kills it.

1052
00:52:20,293 --> 00:52:22,030
Scott: And now suddenly there's a whole bunch of free memory.

1053
00:52:22,131 --> 00:52:24,070
Scott: The Linux kernel basically just reaches into your wallet.

1054
00:52:24,550 --> 00:52:26,810
Scott: It's like we were out of room in this wallet for more cards.

1055
00:52:27,110 --> 00:52:28,930
Scott: And I have a card that has to go in the wallet.

