00:52:29,050 --> 00:52:31,849
Scott: Well, I'm picking a card out of the wallet and I'm throwing it in the shredder.

1057
00:52:32,710 --> 00:52:34,790
Scott: And now we've got cards are all in place again.

1058
00:52:34,970 --> 00:52:37,370
Rym: Now, the thing is, very rarely will the O.M.

1059
00:52:37,450 --> 00:52:43,329
Rym: killer save you because usually it kills something that you wanted to be running or even if it kills stuff you didn't want.

1060
00:52:43,611 --> 00:52:45,810
Rym: Whatever went crazy is like, oh, more RAM.

1061
00:52:46,130 --> 00:52:47,099
Scott: Yeah, goodie.

1062
00:52:47,321 --> 00:52:48,189
Scott: But the thing is, the O.M.

1063
00:52:48,310 --> 00:52:50,430
Scott: killer probably will eventually kill the evil thing.

1064
00:52:50,511 --> 00:52:53,310
Scott: But the thing is, the evil thing is usually something that you want running.

1065
00:52:53,771 --> 00:52:53,912
Rym: Yeah.

1066
00:52:53,932 --> 00:52:56,345
Scott: So pretty much no matter what, you're going to be either.

1067
00:52:56,426 --> 00:52:57,732
Scott: your computer will keep working.

1068
00:52:57,873 --> 00:52:58,074
Scott: Right.

1069
00:52:58,114 --> 00:52:58,556
Scott: And you'll.

1070
00:52:58,898 --> 00:53:05,993
Scott: you'll be able to fix it because the computer will have free memory to be able to connect to it and log in and enter commands to solve the problem, which is great.

1071
00:53:06,516 --> 00:53:09,451
Scott: The problem is, is something that you wanted to keep running is now not running.

1072
00:53:09,472 --> 00:53:12,590
Rym: Well, the two cases I've run into primarily with the O.M.

1073
00:53:12,670 --> 00:53:18,448
Rym: killer and my advice to all of you, a lot of people Google on the Internet looking for what do I do to recover from the O.M.

1074
00:53:18,670 --> 00:53:18,995
Rym: killer?

1075
00:53:19,279 --> 00:53:19,684
Rym: You know what?

1076
00:53:19,745 --> 00:53:20,090
Rym: Reboot.

1077
00:53:20,890 --> 00:53:26,234
